Multi-cue recall (late trials only)

Info: These are all the main analyses split by early/late in the critical round. We define “late” as after trial 10

Participants

  • N = 69
  • This combines the previous dataset (N = 40) with one collected on May 20 (N=29).

Proportion presentation time

The simplest test of rational memory: do people spend more time looking at the cue that they have a stronger memory of? This analysis only considers trials where both cues are seen.

X = multi %>% 
    filter(n_pres >= 2)

X %>% ggplot(aes(strength_first - strength_second, prop_first, color=phase)) +
    stat_summary_bin(fun.data=mean_cl_boot, bins=10) +
    geom_smooth(method='lm')

X %>% filter(phase == "early") %>% lmer(prop_first ~ rel_strength + (rel_strength|wid), data=.) %>% summ
Fixed Effects
Est. S.E. t val. d.f. p
(Intercept) 0.505 0.014 36.257 57.546 0.000
rel_strength 0.034 0.008 4.073 71.253 0.000
p values calculated using Satterthwaite d.f. 
X %>% filter(phase == "late") %>% lmer(prop_first ~ rel_strength + (rel_strength|wid), data=.) %>% summ
Fixed Effects
Est. S.E. t val. d.f. p
(Intercept) 0.507 0.013 40.327 55.800 0.000
rel_strength 0.041 0.008 4.952 47.953 0.000
p values calculated using Satterthwaite d.f.

Note: here and everywhere else, the first regression table is for early and the second is for late.

First presentation duration

Consider only the trials with more than one presentation. Do participants switch away from the first image more quickly when they have a worse memory of it?

X = multi %>% 
    filter(n_pres > 1)

X %>% ggplot(aes(strength_first, first_pres_time, color=phase)) + 
    stat_summary_bin(fun.data=mean_cl_boot, bins=10) +
    geom_smooth(method='lm')

X %>% filter(phase == "early") %>% lmer(first_pres_time ~ strength_first + (strength_first|wid), data=.) %>% summ
Fixed Effects
Est. S.E. t val. d.f. p
(Intercept) 1206.302 65.800 18.333 50.483 0.000
strength_first 1.138 40.907 0.028 20.478 0.978
p values calculated using Satterthwaite d.f. 
X %>% filter(phase == "late") %>% lmer(first_pres_time ~ strength_first + (strength_first|wid), data=.) %>% summ
Fixed Effects
Est. S.E. t val. d.f. p
(Intercept) 1321.978 108.319 12.204 44.395 0.000
strength_first 57.451 28.192 2.038 14.906 0.060
p values calculated using Satterthwaite d.f.

The vanilla regression line is worse, but the mixed effects gives an almost significant result in the correct direction (for the late trials).

Second presentation duration

We can do a similar analysis for the second presentation duration. In this case, however, the duration may depend on the strength of both the first and second cues.

Second-seen strength

X = multi %>% 
    filter(n_pres > 2) %>% 
    mutate(second_pres_time = map_dbl(presentation_times, 2, .default=NaN))

X %>% ggplot(aes(strength_second, second_pres_time, color=phase)) + 
    stat_summary_bin(fun.data=mean_cl_boot, bins=10) +
    geom_smooth(method='lm')

X %>% filter(phase == "early") %>% lmer(second_pres_time ~ strength_second + (1|wid), data=.) %>% summ
Fixed Effects
Est. S.E. t val. d.f. p
(Intercept) 1036.756 93.479 11.091 44.545 0.000
strength_second 48.116 63.740 0.755 177.925 0.451
p values calculated using Satterthwaite d.f. 
X %>% filter(phase == "late") %>% lmer(second_pres_time ~ strength_second + (1|wid), data=.) %>% summ
Fixed Effects
Est. S.E. t val. d.f. p
(Intercept) 1184.827 129.874 9.123 31.164 0.000
strength_second 55.252 60.511 0.913 158.742 0.363
p values calculated using Satterthwaite d.f.

No difference here.

Again, the mixed effects model shows a much larger and more reliable effect in late trials but there isn’t a clear difference in the vanilla regression.

Third fixation - relative strength

Can we push it further?

X = multi %>% 
    filter(n_pres > 3) %>% 
    mutate(third_pres_time = map_dbl(presentation_times, 3, .default=NaN))

X %>% ggplot(aes(rel_strength, third_pres_time, color=phase)) + 
    stat_summary_bin(fun.data=mean_cl_boot, bins=10) +
    geom_smooth(method='lm')

X %>% filter(phase == "early") %>% lmer(third_pres_time ~ rel_strength + (rel_strength|wid), data=.) %>% summ
Fixed Effects
Est. S.E. t val. d.f. p
(Intercept) 1290.048 283.795 4.546 16.315 0.000
rel_strength -86.239 103.770 -0.831 3.718 0.456
p values calculated using Satterthwaite d.f. 
X %>% filter(phase == "late") %>% lmer(third_pres_time ~ rel_strength + (rel_strength|wid), data=.) %>% summ
Fixed Effects
Est. S.E. t val. d.f. p
(Intercept) 1302.073 304.819 4.272 13.538 0.001
rel_strength 381.844 133.555 2.859 10.116 0.017
p values calculated using Satterthwaite d.f.

This one is quite striking!

Discussion

It looks like overall the effects become stronger and more reliable over time.
